***How does a Kanban board work, and how does it help manage workflow?***

	A kanban board is a visual project management tool, utilizing cards, columns, and work-in-progress (WIP) limits to help teams manage workflow, limit WIP, and maximize efficiency. Kanban boards are broken down into five distinct components: visual signals, columns, WIP limits, a commitment point, and a delivery point:

* Visual signals – Visual cards that all projects and work items are written onto. Help for quick visualization.   
* Columns – Each column represents a specific activity that together composes a workflow; can either be very simple or very complex.   
* WIP limits – Maximum number of cards that can be in one column at any given time. When maxed out, the team must work diligently to complete them before they can move on to the next stage in the workflow. WIP limits are critical for exposing bottlenecks and maximising flow.  
* Commitment point – Where customers and teammates put ideas for projects that the team can pick up when ready. The commitment point is the point when an idea is picked up and work starts on the project.  
* Delivery point – The end point of a kanban team’s workflow. Elapsed time between commitment point and delivery point is called the lead time. Teams want to minimize this time as much as possible.

Kanban boards help to establish order, streamline team workflow, expose weaknesses, and boost overall productivity.

***What do the different columns on a Kanban board represent (e.g., Backlog, In Progress, Blocked, Done)?***

	The different columns on a Kanban board represent the different stages of workflow. While different Kanban boards have different columns, the overall essence is the same for the different stages. Some of these stages may include:

* Backlog (To Do) – The backlog of ideas for projects that customers or teammates come up with that are waiting to be picked up and worked on.   
* Up Next – Prioritization of the backlog for what projects have more urgency.  
* Blocked – These tasks distinctly limit or harm the workflow, and teams must work with urgency to undo the blockage.  
* In Progress – The main section of many Kanban boards where it displays the projects currently being worked on. This section is distinctly limited so as to prevent overcrowding and enable streamlined work processes with ample communication and collaboration.   
* Done – These tasks have been completed.

***How do tasks move through the board, and who is responsible for updating them?***

	Tasks move through the board either based on completion of a certain stage, in the case of a project moving from WIP to finished, or a key decision, like when identifying a blockage. Though, generally, tasks are moved throughout the board by the individual or individuals responsible for them. 

***What are the benefits of limiting work in progress (WIP)?***

	By limiting the WIP stage of kanban boards, it forces teams to work diligently on the tasks at hand, not getting caught up by taking on too many projects at once and quickly becoming overwhelmed. It also enables better team collaboration and communication through teams having to quickly work together to minimize the amount of works in progress to begin working on the next critical project.

–

***How does Kanban help manage priorities and avoid overload?***

	Firstly, Kanban avoids overload by incorporating built in limits on works in progress. This is key to enabling team members to directly work on a handful of problems at a time rather than having too many projects that need completion with not enough time. It enables a better management of resources and overall improved operational efficiency. This also helps to manage priorities through either a built in prioritization column, or through what tasks are selected and completed at which times. 

***How can you improve your workflow using Kanban principles?***

	My workflow could be improved through the usage of Kanban principles in the way that it places strict limits on the number of works in progress I can have at any given time. This would help me make better use of my time when working on projects either professionally or personally, also allowing me to reach greater levels of depth when engaging with certain ideas versus taking on too many projects at once and risking completing none of them.
